[Event "The Evergreen Game"]
[Site "Berlin"]
[Date "1852"]
[White "Adolf Anderssen"]
[Black "Jean Dufresne"]
[Result "1-0"]

{Another Anderssen masterpiece, called "The Evergreen" because its brilliance never fades. A wild Evans Gambit with spectacular sacrifices.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 {The Evans Gambit — sacrificing a pawn for rapid development and central control.} Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 6. d4 exd4 7. O-O d3 {Black tries to hold the extra pawn, but this blocks development.} (7... dxc3 {The safer option.} 8. Qb3 Qf6 9. e5 Qg6 10. Nxc3 {White has excellent compensation.}) 8. Qb3 Qf6 9. e5 Qg6 10. Re1 Nge7 11. Ba3 {Preventing Black from castling by targeting the e7 knight's defence of the dark squares.} b5 (11... O-O {Was preferable, getting the king to safety.} 12. Bxe7 Nxe7 {Black would have survived.}) 12. Qxb5 Rb8 13. Qa4 Bb6 14. Nbd2 Bb7 15. Ne4 Qf5 {Black's queen is actively placed but the king is still in the center.} 16. Bxd3 Qh5 17. Nf6+! {A stunning knight sacrifice to open lines against the king.} gxf6 18. exf6 Rg8 {Black tries to hold on.} (18... Kf8 {Trying to escape.} 19. Bg6! fxg6 20. Rad1 {White's attack is decisive.}) 19. Rad1! {Bringing the last piece into the attack. Every white piece is aimed at Black's king.} Qxf3 {Black grabs material, but Anderssen has calculated the finish.} 20. Rxe7+! Nxe7 (20... Kd8 21. Rxd7+ Kc8 22. Rd8# {Mate.}) 21. Qxd7+!! Kxd7 22. Bf5+ Ke8 (22... Kc6 23. Bd7# {Checkmate!}) 23. Bd7+ Kf8 24. Bxe7# {A beautiful double bishop checkmate! The Evergreen Game.} 1-0
